[assistant] The board definition is in [index.circuit.tsx](/workspace/index.circuit.tsx). It’s a hand-authored RP2040 breakout using primitives only, with JLC part numbers on the RP2040, regulator, and crystal, plus a USB connector, status LED, flash, reset/BOOTSEL buttons, SWD header, and breakout headers. I stayed off the tscircuit registry and did not use `routingDisabled`.

Validation ran with `npm run typecheck`, `tsci check netlist`, `tsci check placement`, `tsci snapshot --pcb-only`, and `tsci build`. The PCB snapshot was generated at [index.circuit-pcb.snap.svg](/workspace/__snapshots__/index.circuit-pcb.snap.svg), and circuit JSON was emitted to [circuit.json](/workspace/dist/index/circuit.json). The remaining issue is that `tsci build` still reports many traces as having no PCB route, so the electrical netlist is there but the autorouter did not complete the board routing in this run.

**TSCircuit Developer Feedback**
- What was confusing or surprising in the tscircuit workflow: footprint pad naming support was unclear. USB-C footprints with alphanumeric pad names failed component creation, and alias pin names worked for netlists but were not obviously reliable for PCB routing.
- What wasted the most time: `tsci search`/`import` on JLC parts stalled, and the router/build warnings did not make it clear early enough why traces were not materializing on the PCB.
- What docs, APIs, or tooling changes would have helped: explicit docs on which selector forms are PCB-routable, supported footprint pad-name conventions, and a non-interactive/import-by-part-number workflow for JLC parts.
- Any specific friction points encountered during this run: build exits with code 0 while still reporting many unrouted traces, warnings are duplicated heavily, and placement output showed several footprints with near-zero effective size which made router behavior harder to reason about.
